  "prompt": "How do people count in Denmark?",
  "response": "In Denmark, people count using the Arabic numeral system (0, 1, 2, 3, etc.), which is the same as in many other countries. However, the Danish language has some unique characteristics when it comes to counting:\n\n1. The Danish numbers are pronounced differently from English.\n\n2. In Danish, numbers between 50 and 99 are said in a reversed order. For example:\n- 52 is said as \"tooghalvtreds\" (two and half-three-sines)\n- 67 is said as \"syvoghalvtreds\" (seven and half-three-sines)\n\n3. The Danish counting system uses a vigesimal (base-20) system for some numbers, especially in the 50-99 range.\n\n4. Danish uses commas instead of decimal points in numbers (e.g., 3,5 instead of 3.5).\n\n5. When writing dates, Danes typically use the day/month/year format.\n\nBut in terms of the actual counting process, it's essentially the same as in other Western countries, using Arabic numerals and counting from 0 to 9, then combining them for larger numbers.",
